content: Today I met some of the most accomplished and humble people I’ve ever had the PLEASURE of chatting with.  Each caused me to challenge myself in a way that won’t be obvious to them.

At lunch: family at the next table.  20something year old had an idea and wants to go the startup route.  Parents spent a hour warning about startups.

Taking everything I have to not lean over and say go for it.
The East Village is having a moment with new restaurants and it’s great to see.
Seen at the Museum of Street Art @ the CitizenM Bowery. https://t.co/CzwwetMAO3

Who are the (pre)seedAI security startups?  Who is building in the space?

Want to talk w/founders about the problems they are seeing and solving.  Why that problem, why not something else, where they want to go, how broad they will go in solving issues w/data, prompts, & models.
One of my favorite burgers is from a gas station near Jay, Florida. https://t.co/tbjfwdkZXG
Rainy day is a perfect day at the @metmuseum.  Good exhibit at the @met_costume.

Met a founder this morning preparing to raise seed asking great questions from market risk to gtm to investor relations.  Way more prepared than when I raised. Got connected to me through @ColumbiaEship.

OH  at a hotel:  I mapquested it.

Kudos to MapQuest for keeping on

I'm just a boy, standing in front of a founder, trying to get an allocation in their first raise. I'm chasing too deals right now harder than I've chased any.  You seed investors work hard.  Big shout out to @jefielding and others.
Wow must be capital call season.  Good to see deals getting funded, funds making calls, and deals still moving. https://t.co/fWPR8aLgHM

“Can we us AI tools help with our project” asked one of my grad students.

I encourage it. By using AI tools students learn how to leverage resources available to them, to adopt new solutions in a changing world, and where these solutions have limitations.

You see what can be learned and refined taking the journey multiple times.

Stop thinking startups are good operating companies and romanticizing them.

They do one thing well and everything else is ignored while trying to survive.  

They are not a model for you to follow to operate a company, they are a cautionary tale.
“Good news, we landed early” is always followed by “we’ll be parked here while we wait for a gate” which is another way of saying  “we’ll be on time or late but not actually early”

The truest statement of all "revenue solves a lot of problems".

ChatGPT told me GPT-3 is open source. 

I corrected it, asked the same question and it corrected the answer.

It told me BERT was open source. I told it I invented BERT and it's not open source. It apologized and said it's not open source (it actually is).

I'm getting more cold emails from new funds than I've ever seen. On one hand, love the increased deal flow and on the other I'm surprised by how many new funds are popping up.
People spend so much time trying to figure out what their boss wants instead of just asking.  I rather someone ask me instead of guessing, wasting time, and get it wrong.

I hate to admit it. I like the "for you" feed. It's chaotic, wild, unpredictable, interesting, giving me new people to read, new thoughts to follow up on.

Amazing difference in two firms this week.  

Firm 1: annual updates, quarterly out reach, adhoc touch points when markets are choppy.

Firm 2: nothing.

Keep in touch with investors. You have one check from me but will you get another, will I send deal flow, or recommend you?
Lots of support. Some shills, wannabes, and well meaning but never will be people but lots of people helping each other.  I don’t see this level on tech on the deal side..just the practitioner side.
People work hard.  Started with @sweatystartup and looked at his followers and where he commented.  These people work hard on deal flow and financials.
A lot of people who will make bad deals because they are eager to be business owners or investors.  I hope the best for them.
Fell into a new corner of twitter full of people acquiring small businesses and talking storage units.  Some random thoughts:

There is investor money out there. No matter what you hear. Wires being sent and deals being done. I did my first of '23 already. Have realistic expectations and a solid plan for going through rough times.

Silicon Valley 2012: I want to be a product manager

Silicon Valley 2016: I want to be a founder

Silicon Valley 2020:  I want to be an angel

Silicon Valley 2021: I want to be at the forefront of web3

Silicon Valley 2023: I want a stable job

Talked to lots of new founders last week. While tough economies allow great companies to rise, many seem to forget it’s still a tough ride and time.  Startups are never easy especially in down markets. The basics matter so get them right, fast.
